snippet.textDisplay:
Hold up, you stopped watching Westworld because of a comment made jokingly about the director's love-hate relationship to fan theories? That sounds really harsh. As a creator, I think it felt pretty spot-on.
For example, I GM TTRPG's. I love it when the players figure things out or handle situations in ways I couldn't even dream of. As the director said, it shows that they're interested and invested in your creative work. But at the same time sometimes, just sometimes you want to make things in a certain way, you get a grand vision, you set things up for a specific payoff. Which can be diminished by how it is processed or "consumed". This can feel like a failure on your part.
TTRPG's are not a perfect comparison, because it's a two-way street of creativity while traditional storytelling mediums are more one-way. But it's close enough.
I think most creators struggle with coming to terms with this love-hate relationship. In the end all you can do is accepting that you cannot create the perfect entertainment for everyone out there.

snippet.textDisplay:
I have Rick ideology on asking questions and honestly? It does sucks for a variety of reasons. When I find plot holes/inconsistencies while everyone is contempt to ignore them it frustrates me. I don't do it with everything and if they are small/insignificant enough I can turn off focusing on it. The disappointment comes from either poor writing or the fact that those around me can ignore it and will ignore it. Basically said people make claims of people who ask questions those who are "over thinking, over analyzing, focusing on the bad instead of the good" when it's not that it's just seeing jarring problems or like theorists finding a possible message/hint/foreshadowing many ignore or don't notice.


I just want well written media but if I question the quality on something that is popular with people who defend it because "I LikE ThE THiNg sO iT cAn'T bE baD" then it's disheartening. Media quality can suffer when people do not challenge what they engage in. Also, if I have to turn my mind off to enjoy media then it's not good media imo. There should not be plot points I have to question the validity of but not everyone agrees. To me this is one of the biggest problems with thinking beyond the media engagement and asking questions. This unique kind of frustration when bad writing is justified or accepted because of the name attached to it (this does not pertain to anything RaM but just other media I enjoy like video games).

However, I agree that there's a mid point to ask questions or not. Questions should be asked when issues are in the narrative but some are intentional. It's when it's not and it creates problems when it's a problem and questions should be asked.

Ones that neither Rick nor Jerry could decide if it went too far or not, it would create the same kind of disgusted reaction, and I’m guessing it would make both of the two never want to see that cat again, while knowing they can’t punish the cat for something that was ultimately the right thing to do, even if it was absolutely horrific. It wouldn’t be too hard to freak Rick out like that either, because while he has killed too many times to count, it always takes only around a minute at best. Rick, despite how often he murders, never takes over a few minutes doing it.

I’m thinking this cat really fucked some guys up.
